Sheryl Sandberg: Facebook's first lady
Before Sheryl Sandberg joined Facebook or Google, she was chief of staff to US Secretary of the Treasury, Larry Summers. That she started out in politics comes as little surprise.
Sheryl Sandberg advises women to wilfully ignore the glass ceiling, and to refuse to modify their ambitions in order to accommodate family plans Photo: Bloomberg	By Katherine Rushton, Media, Telecoms and Technology Editor
8:22PM BST 15 Apr 2013
Follow Comments
The 43-year old who, as Facebook’s chief operating officer, ranks as one of the most influential women in business, is masterful at charming her crowd whilst giving very little away.
Yesterday, on a rare visit to the social network’s headquarters in Britain, all coiffed hair and stylish outfit, she rattled off stats and polished sound bites with barely an um or an er.
Facebook is “the most engaging platform this planet has ever seen”, she claimed. Its new “Home” product, which allows people to turn the fronts of their mobiles in into a Facebook newsfeed, is “as important if not more important than television”.
In America, one out of every four minutes spent on smartphones is spent on Facebook. Did she mention that 63pc of users in Europe check into Facebook at least once a day?
Next came a dose of flattery. Facebook chose London as the site of its first engineering centre outside America “to take advantage of what is a very strong pool of technical candidates”. Europe is “really important to Facebook. We are growing and expanding and investing”.
