She doesn’t get here more than once a year, a member of her entourage explains, but that’s because she doesn’t like being away from her children.
Ms Sandberg will spend part of her visit to Britain promoting her new book, Lean In, which advises women to wilfully ignore the glass ceiling, and to refuse to modify their ambitions in order to accommodate family plans. The book has sparked controversy, with critics claiming that it is all very well to take that view when you have more than $400m in Facebook stock and a pay package of more than $30m a year. Ms Sandberg said yesterday she was “surprised by how many people paid attention” but was grateful for debate “because I don’t know of anything that changes without heated debate on both sides”.
Many have interpreted Lean In as a political tract designed to ease her route back into the sphere where she began her career. But Ms Sandberg said yesterday that she had no such plans. “I’m not [leaving]. I love my job. I wrote this book because, along with my job, I’m watching what’s happening – or not happening”.
Facebook’s investors would be rattled by a Sandberg departure. Alongside founder, Mark Zuckerberg, Ms Sandberg is the main face of the company. The possibility of her departure is listed in the “risk factors” section of its Securities Exchange Commission filings.
However, shareholders might also be concerned that Ms Sandberg is spending so much energy campaigning for seismic social change, less than a year on from Facebook’s disastrous flotation. Shares in the company were trading at $26.59 in New York yesterday afternoon, well below its $38-a-share initial public offering.
One of the biggest issues the company has faced is the rapid increase in mobile users, which has outpaced the advances Facebook has made in monetising them through advertising.
“To say that mobile is important to Facebook is the biggest under exaggeration of all time,” Ms Sandberg said yesterday. “We now have a computers in our pockets that are 100 times more powerful than the computer that sent the first man to the moon in the year I was born.”
Facebook’s attempts to harness that shift have been controversial, but Ms Sandberg said the company would not back away from its strategy of serving up ads based on detailed user information.
Facebook Home goes a step further, by turning the fronts of users’ smartphones into a Facebook “feed”, featuring ads and updates from friends. It is available on devices that run on Google’s Android operating system, but not Apple’s iPhones and iPads.
Ms Sandberg came the closest yet to declaring a Facebook alliance with Google, and distancing the company from Apple.
“Home is based on the openness of Android,” she said. “Apple controls its interfaces...Just look at Android phones - there is a huge range of them. The iPhone always looks like the iPhone.
“We are going to going to continue to develop for both [but] it is true that Android allows us to develop a far more immersive Facebook experience.”
She refused to disclose how Facebook’s discussions with Apple went, insisting blandly that they have a “very good relationship”. But in the world of technology giants, it feels like the ghost of a new battle line has been drawn - just with deft, political diplomacy. Facebook
